Full Text: The message of this song which has helped me become more comfortable with my sexuality.\Because its a great song and a song that I can help pick me up at times when I'm feeling down especially if its due to someone's homophobia or if I'm worrying about what others might think of my sexuality.\Its an upbeat encouraging song aimed at gay people but the lyrics aren't too specific so some people could relate to it for other reasons. I really like its lyrics and too and Joey does have a good voice.\I first listened to this track when I was on the bus back home from town after someone had been homophobic towards me. I wanted to listen to some music to cheer me up and had heard about this song so I decided to give it a listen. I really enjoyed listening to it and its lyrics and music video made me feel better and the song has helped me to feel more comfortable about my sexuality and it has helped me feel more confident about being open about who I am. I selected 'enjoy' rather than 'really enjoy' because this song may mean a lot to me but I feel its not as strong as it could have been. I feel like the production and pacing could be better in places and the bridge and I feel like more could have been done with the bridge and final chorus. Its not a song I go back to that often but I still really like this song and appreciate how it has helped me. I'm also still not quite as confident about being open about my sexuality either so listening to this does still help me.

Full Text: Period abroad at university with the impending end of my relationship with a boy from America I really like the song and it gives me bittersweet nostalgia about a significant period of my life. Nostalgia that lets me reflect on the choices I have made and how I have grown as a person I really love the lyrics Yes. It was a meaningful song and I really connected with the lyrics several years ago when I was going through the imminent end of my relationship. The song is based on the book by John Green about two young people with cancer and the eventual death of one of the protagonists. The song covers how "pain demands to be felt" and how everything that was once meaningful will stop as if it never mattered. I really connected to the bargaining aspect of the grieving process (about how I will "be better if you stay"). As I knew that once my boyfriend and I left the country that we would never see each other again. Almost like a bereavement. It allowed me to connect to and express my emotions that I found difficult to give words to.

Full Text: Haha, that this is a track from one of the most expensive records I ever bought... I have this song on a 5x record box set which cost $130 a few years ago. I love this band, they only ever released weird bootleg live albums, without ever making a 'proper' album. This is my favourite song of theirs, and I have at least ten versions of it- they're all full of distortion and noise, often with bad sound quality and people talking, feedback, shambolic performances etc but it all adds to the strange chaotic wildness of the band. Even though it's slow track, the lo-fi way that it's recorded and the sort of unpredictable character of all of this band's recordings mean that its kind of exciting, it feels as if the wheels might fall off and it collapse, or it might manage to wobble along into something amazing. Because I have a bunch of different versions of this track by the same band, it means I'm not completely certain what will happen next. It's interesting, I feel like I have a relationship with this song rather than the particular version I'm listening to, which comes out differently in the many different versions that I have on my device, as well as some other versions that exist on Youtube, and more versions I haven't ever heard but might do in the future... its a really distinctive track, but at the same time, the wild noisy different versions mean that there could be other recordings of the same track by the same band that would be recognisably the same but also brilliantly different.

Reminds me of childhood. It's from the soundtrack to a film that was released when I was a child, based in the city I grew up in. This was on the radio A LOT when I was young!

I rediscovered it about 6 years ago, but ultimately it's an album that everyone from a certain part of the world is familiar with. It starts off quite mournful but it's got a lot of energy towards the end.Again, it's just something everyone would know and maybe even be a little sick of... Reminds me of being a child, growing up in a city that looks very different now to how it did when the song was released (1991), so it's very nostalgic. It has been a very long time since I listened to this song. There was a time when I used to think Jeff Buckley was brilliant, but these days I don't feel very connected to his music. Listening to it I very much feel a melancholic longing back to my younger days when my life was simple enough that I could indulge in "buckleyesce" sensitivities. I used to be very much in that mindset, but growing older has rearranged my emotional priorities.  To be clear I want to point out that I do not use a listening device, I listen to all my music on youtube and do not make playlists. In order to get random song selection I scrolled down in my youtube suggestion list to the first song suggestion that I actually have listened to before. To my surprise, this came up. So I did not save it to my device, however I did do so many years ago when I first heard it. The reason back then was basically for research purposes (ie learning the parts), as I play guitar myself and thought it was brilliantly sung and played.


 I have mixed feelings with it, there's defenitely a sense of beauty in the performance and delivery, but at the same time the emotional delivery seem less relevant in my life today. Full Text: How do these songs end up in my suggested list! I haven't listened to it for so long, yet somehow youtube knows this is my music. I listened to Bob Dylan when I was quite young, finding the records in my dad's record collection, and got myself familiar on the guitar playing many of his songs. I have also listened to Johnny Cash a lot and like his delivery very much. The type of vibe that this performance gives off is one that comes very easy for me to create with my own music, although I do prefer a more european sound. I do like this song a lot;  the original recording of it by Bob Dylan has one of my all time favorite picking patterns. This particular performance is nice because Bob Dylan starts off singing his verse in his (at that time) regular style, after which Cash gives a very heartfelt rendition of his verse, changing the mood. Upon experiencing the delivery by Cash, Dylan subsequently adapts his delivery of the next verse to a similar passionate style. Again, not recently saved, but saved when I first heard it. I like this song and like the cooperation of the two musicians whom I both like.  Let's be honest, it is kind of a boring song if your not in the mood for it. But it is one that has become part of my history. I must say I was expecting to find songs that I have been listening to more recently and that I feel more emotionally connected to at this very moment, which would have perhaps made for more interesting writing, but song selection was definitely random and unexpected. The original recording of this song has one of my favorite picking patterns. As far as playing this myself, of all of Dylan's songs (of which I learned, and forgotten, many) this is in the top few songs that have stayed with me and I still enjoy playing. So it must appeal to me in a special way. Although I have never given this any thought conciously, I must say the theme of distant love is definitely one that I know myself to be drawn to.

Yes, it is linked to my children and various activities we have participated in with a Moana theme (parties, cinema trip, listening to the soundtrack on long journeys). Full Text: I love the energy and rhythmicity of it. As soon as it started, I was bouncing around in my chair! I've seen the band play live, and when they perform this piece the percussionist sits at the front of the stage, and strikes a variety of objects extremely rapidly all the way through the piece, to a very tight and well-defined rhythm. I can visualise the physical effort and control he displays, and that feeds into my experience of the piece. But it's also generally a very lively and joyful piece -- I smile when I hear it -- so I don't feel the percussionist's physical effort as a strain, as such: more like extremely energetic dancing. I bought the CD at a gig by the Graham Fitkin band. I wanted to have the music to listen to, because I enjoy the pieces per se -- but it also lets me carry a bit of the memory of the gig around with me. As I mentioned above: energy, rhythmicity, joyfulness, memories of great nights spent watching the band. I feel I have a very physical relationship with this track, because of the driving energy of the rhythms and my memories of the percussionist playing. I'm also a keen follower of Graham Fitkin and his music, so when I hear this track (or indeed any of his) it reminds me of that part of my musical identity: amongst the many things that I am as a musical being, I identify as a "Graham Fitkin fan", and this piece somehow serves to strengthen the relationship I feel with Graham (or at least his public persona) and his music.

Full Text: I haven't listened to this for a long time! I love Bartok, and particularly enjoy the folk influence in his rhythms, melodies and harmonies, but for various reasons this I haven't put this on for a while. I trained as a classical musician during my teenage years, and used to listen to a lot of classical music then -- this piece included. I remember having very strong experiences listening to this piece, particularly the last movement: real rushes of overwhelming joy and excitement. I bought the CD many years ago, and it was one of a group of particularly loved CDs that I uploaded to my iPod when I was first given it. Strong rhythm, folk influences on melody and harmony, contrapuntal interest, subtle and beautiful orchestration. It reminds me very much of the intense musical experiences I used to have listening to classical music as a young person. These days, I tend to listen to classical music when working or in the background; in those days I spent a lot more time actually sitting and listening to music as a primary activity, and I often had very strong experiences during those listening sessions.
